<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">Judges 8:1-35</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="21">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="35">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">Then the men of E&acute;phra&middot;im said to him: “What sort of thing is this that you have done to us in not calling us when you went to fight against Mid&acute;i&middot;an?” And they vehemently tried to pick a quarrel with him.</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">Finally he said to them: “What now have I done in comparison with <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>? Are not the gleanings of E&acute;phra&middot;im better than the grape gathering of Abi-e&acute;zer?</span> <a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">It was into <span class="smallcaps">YOUR</span> hand that God gave Mid&acute;i&middot;an’s princes O&acute;reb and Ze&acute;eb, and what have I been able to do in comparison with <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>?” It was then that their spirit calmed down toward him when he spoke this word.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">Eventually Gid&acute;e&middot;on came to the Jordan, crossing it, he and the three hundred men that were with him, tired but keeping up the pursuit.</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">Later he said to the men of Suc&acute;coth: “Please give round loaves of bread to the people that are following my steps, for they are tired and I am chasing after Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na, the kings of Mid&acute;i&middot;an.”</span> <a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">But the princes of Suc&acute;coth said: “Are the palms of Ze&acute;bah and of Zal&middot;mun&acute;na already in your hand so that bread has to be given to your army?”</span> <a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">At this Gid&acute;e&middot;on said: “That is why when Jehovah gives Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na into my hand, I shall certainly give <span class="smallcaps">YOUR</span> flesh a threshing with the thorns of the wilderness and the briers.”</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">And he continued on his way up from there to Pe&middot;nu&acute;el and went speaking to them in this same manner, but the men of Pe&middot;nu&acute;el answered him just as the men of Suc&acute;coth had answered.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">Hence he said also to the men of Pe&middot;nu&acute;el: “When I return in peace, I shall pull down this tower.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">Now Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na were in Kar&acute;kor, and their camps with them, about fifteen thousand being all who were left over out of the entire camp of the Easterners; and those already fallen were a hundred and twenty thousand men who used to draw the sword.</span> <a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">And Gid&acute;e&middot;on continued on up by the way of those residing in tents to the east of No&acute;bah and Jog&acute;be&middot;hah and began to strike the camp while the camp happened to be off guard.</span> <a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">When Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na took to flight, he at once went in pursuit of them and got to capture Mid&acute;i&middot;an’s two kings, Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na; and he drove all the camp into trembling.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">And Gid&acute;e&middot;on the son of Jo&acute;ash began his return from the war by the pass that goes up to He&acute;res.</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">En route he captured a young man of the men of Suc&acute;coth and made inquiries of him. So he wrote out for him the names of the princes of Suc&acute;coth and its older men, seventy-seven men.</span> <a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">With that he went to the men of Suc&acute;coth and said: “Here are Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na respecting whom <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> taunted me, saying, ‘Are the palms of Ze&acute;bah and of Zal&middot;mun&acute;na already in your hand so that bread has to be given to your tired-out men?’”</span> <a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">Then he took the older men of the city and thorns of the wilderness and briers, and with them he put the men of Suc&acute;coth through an experience.</span> <a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">And the tower of Pe&middot;nu&acute;el he pulled down, and he proceeded to kill the men of the city.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">He now said to Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na: “What sort of men were they whom <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> killed in Ta&acute;bor?” To this they said: “As you are, so were they, each one, like the sons of a king in form.”</span> <a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">At that he said: “They were my brothers, the sons of my mother. As Jehovah lives, if <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> had preserved them alive, I would not have to kill <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>.”</span> <a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">Then he said to Je&acute;ther his firstborn: “Get up, kill them.” And the young man did not draw his sword, because he was afraid, for he was yet a young man.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">So Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na said: “Get up yourself and assault us, for as a man is, so is his mightiness.” Accordingly Gid&acute;e&middot;on got up and killed Ze&acute;bah and Zal&middot;mun&acute;na and took the moon-shaped ornaments that were on the necks of their camels.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">Later the men of Israel said to Gid&acute;e&middot;on: “Rule over us, you and your son and your grandson as well, for you have saved us out of the hand of Mid&acute;i&middot;an.”</span> <a name="bk23" class="vsAnchor">23</a>
       <span id="vs23">But Gid&acute;e&middot;on said to them: “I myself shall not rule over <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, nor will my son rule over <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>. Jehovah is the one who will rule over <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>.”</span> <a name="bk24" class="vsAnchor">24</a>
       <span id="vs24">And Gid&acute;e&middot;on went on to say to them: “Let me make a request of <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>: Give me, each one of <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, the nose ring of his booty.” (For they had nose rings of gold, because they were Ish&acute;ma&middot;el&middot;ites.)</span> <a name="bk25" class="vsAnchor">25</a>
       <span id="vs25">Then they said: “We shall surely give them.” With that they spread out a mantle and went throwing each one the nose ring of his booty into it.</span> <a name="bk26" class="vsAnchor">26</a>
       <span id="vs26">And the weight of the nose rings of gold that he had requested amounted to one thousand seven hundred gold shekels, besides the moon-shaped ornaments and the eardrops and the garments of wool dyed reddish purple that were upon the kings of Mid&acute;i&middot;an and besides the necklaces that were on the necks of the camels.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk27" class="vsAnchor">27</a>
       <span id="vs27">And Gid&acute;e&middot;on proceeded to make it into an eph&acute;od and to exhibit it in his city Oph&acute;rah; and all Israel began to have immoral intercourse with it there, so that it served as a snare to Gid&acute;e&middot;on and to his household.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk28" class="vsAnchor">28</a>
       <span id="vs28">Thus Mid&acute;i&middot;an was subdued before the sons of Israel, and they did not lift up their head anymore; and the land had no further disturbance for forty years in the days of Gid&acute;e&middot;on.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk29" class="vsAnchor">29</a>
       <span id="vs29">And Jer&middot;ub&middot;ba&acute;al the son of Jo&acute;ash went his way and continued to dwell in his house.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk30" class="vsAnchor">30</a>
       <span id="vs30">And Gid&acute;e&middot;on came to have seventy sons that issued out of his upper thigh, for he came to have many wives.</span> <a name="bk31" class="vsAnchor">31</a>
       <span id="vs31">As for the concubine of his that was in She&acute;chem, she too bore him a son. So he named him A&middot;bim&acute;e&middot;lech.</span> <a name="bk32" class="vsAnchor">32</a>
       <span id="vs32">Eventually Gid&acute;e&middot;on the son of Jo&acute;ash died at a good old age and was buried in the burial place of Jo&acute;ash his father in Oph&acute;rah of the Abi-ez&acute;rites.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk33" class="vsAnchor">33</a>
       <span id="vs33">And it came about that as soon as Gid&acute;e&middot;on had died the sons of Israel again took up having immoral intercourse with the Ba&acute;als, so that they appointed Ba&acute;al-be&acute;rith as their god.</span> <a name="bk34" class="vsAnchor">34</a>
       <span id="vs34">And the sons of Israel did not remember Jehovah their God, who had delivered them out of the hand of all their enemies round about;</span> <a name="bk35" class="vsAnchor">35</a>
       <span id="vs35">and they did not exercise loving-kindness toward the household of Jer&middot;ub&middot;ba&acute;al, Gid&acute;e&middot;on, in return for all the goodness that he had exercised toward Israel.</span>
</p>
</form>

